nodes.prompt:
You are screening recent papers for whether they would change a clinical guideline for {{ context.initial.disease_name }}.

What the guideline ALREADY says (current synthesis):
{{ context.gsd-search.current_guidance }}

Recent candidate papers (pmid, title, journal, year, abstract):
{{ context.gsd-search.candidates }}

For EACH candidate, return: pmid, change_probability (0..1 — the chance it adds or CHANGES something that is NOT already in the synthesis above; a paper that merely restates current guidance scores LOW), and a one-line why. Be sceptical — most papers change nothing. Use only the pmids given; never invent.

You are proposing evidence-based UPDATES to a clinical guideline for {{ context.initial.disease_name }}.

What the guideline ALREADY says (do NOT restate what is already here — only go beyond it):
{{ context.gsd-search.current_guidance }}

Guideline sections you may target (use these ids for target_section):
{{ context.gsd-search.sections }}

Candidate papers (pmid, title, journal, year, abstract):
{{ context.gsd-search.candidates }}

Triage scores (change_probability per pmid):
{{ context.gsd-triage.papers }}

For papers that GENUINELY add or change something not already in the guidance (high change_probability), propose a delta: kind (addition / modification), target_section (one of the ids above), title, summary, rationale (state explicitly what is new vs current guidance), evidence (strong/moderate/limited), citations (the paper's pmid(s)), source_pmid. If NOTHING genuinely changes the guideline, return an EMPTY suggestions list — that is the correct, common answer. Cite only the candidate pmids; never invent.
